JGE321H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Diverse approaches to environmental issues in a variety of multicultural settings are introduced, compared and analyzed, using case studies. Perspectives on environmental management will be discussed as they emerge from contexts such as Latin America, Asia, or Africa.
JGE321H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online per the meeting schedule. Approximately 4-6 lectures throughout the term will be live-streamed and involve discussion/questions; attendance is strongly encouraged during these live lectures. All lectures, however, will be posted for asynchronous viewing.

JGE331H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Introduction to and critical evaluation of major ideas and conceptual traditions underpinning environmental and natural resource politics and regulation. Topics include: parks and protected areas, market-based environmental regulation, property rights and conservation, Malthusianism, and biodiversity conservation. Emphasis is placed on critical reading of primary texts.
JGE331H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: All lectures will be live-streamed and recorded (permitting synchronous live participation for students either in person or online, but also asynchronous self-paced engagement with the lectures).
